TY  - JOUR
T1  - Shifting Paradigms for Sustainable Development: Implications for Management Theory and Research
AU  - Gladwin, Thomas N.
AU  - Kennelly, James J.
AU  - Krause, Tara-Shelomith
Y1  - 1995/10/01
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1995.9512280024
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1995.9512280024
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 874
EP  - 907
VL  - 20
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Modern management theory is constricted by a fractured epistemology. which separates humanity from nature and truth from morality. Reintegration is necessary if organizational science is to support ecologically and socially sustainable development. This article posits requisites of such development and rejects the paradigms of conventional technocentrism and antithetical ecocentrism on grounds of incongruence. A more fruitful integrative paradigm of ?sustaincentrism? is then articulated, and implications for organizational science are generated as if sustainability, extended community, and our Academy mattered.
